```
Click Save and Finish
âœ… Jenkins setup is now complete!




ğŸ§± Create Your First Jenkins Job
ğŸ¯ Goal:
Run a simple â€œHello Worldâ€ job to verify Jenkins is working.

Step 1: Create a New Job
    1. Go to Jenkins dashboard.
    2. Click â€œNew Itemâ€
    3. Enter an item name:
        ```
        First-Jenkins-Job
        ```
    4. Select Freestyle project
    5. Click OK


Step 2: Configure the Job
    1. In the General section, add a short description:
    2. Scroll down to Build section â†’ click Add build step â†’ select Execute shell
    3. Enter this command:
        ```
        echo "This is my 1st-job" > jenkins.txt
        ```


Step 3: Save and Build  
    . Click Save
    . Then click Build Now
Youâ€™ll see a build in progress under Build History.


Step 4: View Console Output
    . Click on the build number (e.g., #1)
    . Select Console Output
    You should see:
    ```
    This is my 1st-job
    Finished: SUCCESS
    ```




ğŸ§± Verify Workspace Folder and Job Output (Server Side)
When you run a Jenkins job, Jenkins creates a workspace directory where all the jobâ€™s files and scripts are executed.


1ï¸âƒ£ Check Jenkins workspace directory
Jenkins stores all job-related data under:
```
/var/lib/jenkins/
```

You should see folders like:
```
jobs  nodes  plugins  secrets  updates  workspace
```

2ï¸âƒ£ Check if workspace folder exists
```
ls /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/
```

If youâ€™ve created a job named 1st-job, you should see:

```
1st-job
```


3ï¸âƒ£ Go inside your jobâ€™s workspace
```
cd /var/lib/jenkins/workspace/1st-Job
ls
```



âœ… Verification Complete
This confirms:
    1. Jenkins created the workspace directory
    2. Your job executed successfully
    3. You can view the jobâ€™s console output from the terminal itself



ğŸ§° Troubleshooting
| Problem                             | Solution                                          |
| ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| Jenkins not accessible on port 8080 | Check firewall: `sudo ufw allow 8080`             |
| Jenkins failed to start             | Run: `sudo systemctl restart jenkins`             |
| Java version error                  | Verify: `java -version` (must be â‰¥ 11)            |
| Plugin installation stuck           | Restart Jenkins: `sudo systemctl restart jenkins` |



